73rd Avenue, north side, at 179th Street, showing the colonial Brinkerhoff House, later known as the Skidmore Homestead. The portico was later removed. View 3 shows William Linder at the well, near the east end of the house. Views 1, 2: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection  1922
View 3: P. L. Sperr  March 31, 1927

73rd Avenue, north side, at 179th Street, showing the Brinkerhoff farmhouse, built about 1700. Views 3 and 4 show the front portico gone. The property was owned by Hoagland in 1860; by J. Diehl in 1873; and by Schleider in 1891-1900.

Views 1,2,4: Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

73rd Avenue, north side, at 179th Street, showing the Brinkerhoff House, later the Skidmore House, built about 1700. The house was owned by Hoagland in 1860; by J. Diehl in 1873; and by Schleider from 1891 to 1909. 73rd Avenue was formely Black Stump Road.

Eugene L. Armbruster  Collection
1922

73rd Avenue, north side, at 179th Street, showing the Brinkerhoff house, the lower half of which is stone and the upper shingled. It was also known as the Skidmore house and the J. Diehl house. 73rd Avenue is the former Black Stump Road.

Eugene L. Armbruster Collection

73rd Avenue, north side, at 179th Street, showing the old Brinkerhoff Homestead, built about 1700. Later it was known as the Skidmore house and also the J. Diehl house. The latter owned it in 1873. In 1891-1909 it was on the 38-acre farm of Schleider.

P. L. Sperr
